# Mastering TypeScript Generics: A Practical Guide

Generics are one of TypeScript's most powerful features, enabling you to write flexible, reusable code while maintaining type safety. Let's dive deep into how to use them effectively.

## What Are Generics?

Generics allow you to write code that works with multiple types while preserving type information. Think of them as "type parameters" that get filled in when you use the code.

## Basic Generic Function

```typescript
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
  return arg
}

const result = identity<string>('hello')
const num = identity<number>(42)
```

## Generic Interfaces

```typescript
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T
  status: number
  message: string
}

interface User {
  id: string
  name: string
}

const response: ApiResponse<User> = {
  data: { id: '1', name: 'John' },
  status: 200,
  message: 'Success'
}
```

## Generic Constraints

Use constraints to limit what types can be used:

```typescript
interface HasId {
  id: string
}

function findById<T extends HasId>(items: T[], id: string): T | undefined {
  return items.find(item => item.id === id)
}
```

## Real-World Example: Type-Safe API Client

```typescript
class ApiClient {
  async get<T>(url: string): Promise<T> {
    const response = await fetch(url)
    return response.json()
  }

  async post<T, D>(url: string, data: D): Promise<T> {
    const response = await fetch(url, {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(data)
    })
    return response.json()
  }
}

const client = new ApiClient()
const user = await client.get<User>('/api/users/1')
const newPost = await client.post<Post, CreatePostData>('/api/posts', {
  title: 'New Post',
  content: 'Content here'
})
```

## Advanced Patterns

### Mapped Types with Generics

```typescript
type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [P in keyof T]: T[P]
}

type Partial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P]
}
```

## Conclusion

Generics are essential for writing maintainable TypeScript code. Start with simple examples and gradually incorporate more advanced patterns as you become comfortable with the basics.

# Building Type-Safe REST APIs with TypeScript

Type safety isn't just for frontend code. Let's build a fully type-safe REST API that catches errors at compile time.

## Project Setup

```bash
npm init -y
npm install express zod
npm install -D typescript @types/node @types/express tsx
```

## Schema Validation with Zod

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod'

const CreateUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email(),
  name: z.string().min(2),
  age: z.number().int().positive().optional(),
})

type CreateUserInput = z.infer<typeof CreateUserSchema>
```

## Type-Safe Route Handlers

```typescript
import express from 'express'
import type { Request, Response } from 'express'

const app = express()

app.post('/users', async (
  req: Request<{}, {}, CreateUserInput>,
  res: Response
) => {
  const result = CreateUserSchema.safeParse(req.body)

  if (!result.success) {
    return res.status(400).json({ errors: result.error })
  }

  const user = await createUser(result.data)
  res.json(user)
})
```

## Middleware for Validation

```typescript
import type { RequestHandler } from 'express'

function validate<T>(schema: z.ZodSchema<T>): RequestHandler {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    const result = schema.safeParse(req.body)
    if (!result.success) {
      return res.status(400).json({ errors: result.error })
    }
    req.body = result.data
    next()
  }
}

app.post('/users', validate(CreateUserSchema), async (req, res) => {
  const user = await createUser(req.body)
  res.json(user)
})
```

## End-to-End Type Safety

```typescript
type ApiRoutes = {
  'POST /users': {
    body: CreateUserInput
    response: User
  }
  'GET /users/:id': {
    params: { id: string }
    response: User
  }
}
```

## Conclusion

Type safety throughout your API stack catches bugs early and improves developer experience significantly.

# Advanced CSS Grid Techniques for Modern Layouts

CSS Grid has revolutionized how we build layouts. Let's explore advanced techniques for creating complex, responsive designs.

## Named Grid Lines

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: [sidebar-start] 250px [sidebar-end main-start] 1fr [main-end];
  grid-template-rows: [header-start] auto [header-end content-start] 1fr [content-end];
}

.sidebar {
  grid-column: sidebar-start / sidebar-end;
  grid-row: content-start / content-end;
}
```

## Grid Template Areas

```css
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header header"
    "sidebar main aside"
    "footer footer footer";
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr 200px;
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  min-height: 100vh;
}

.header { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.main { grid-area: main; }
.aside { grid-area: aside; }
.footer { grid-area: footer; }
```

## Auto-Fit and Auto-Fill

```css
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  gap: 1rem;
}
```

## Subgrid

```css
.parent {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 1rem;
}

.child {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: subgrid;
  grid-column: span 3;
}
```

## Responsive Grid Without Media Queries

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(min(250px, 100%), 1fr));
  gap: clamp(1rem, 3vw, 2rem);
}
```

## Conclusion

CSS Grid provides powerful tools for creating flexible, maintainable layouts. Master these techniques to build better user interfaces.
